%S A396609 2,5,83,373,673,3023,5087,14939,149119,273773,1139843,1162867,4758973,
%T A396609 13227197,24246133,32662649,183717409,263740693,1800536173
%N A396609 Prime numbers whose nearest prime distance in the Ulam spiral exceeds that of every smaller prime number.
%C A396609 The nearest prime squared distance of the terms in the sequence are always of the form d=a^2+b^2 (a, b nonnegative integers) with d even and with the only exception being d=1, because in the spiral the number in cell (x,y) has the same parity as x+y, giving a checkerboard coloring, so two cells at a squared distance d have the same color iff d is even. Hence two primes can only be at a distance d apart when d is even with the only exception being d=1 because of the even prime 2.
%H A396609 Shreyans Jain, <a href="/A396609/a396609.py.txt">Python program</a>
%e A396609 a(2) = 5: since a(1) = 2 is at a distance of 1 from its closest prime 3, and the prime 3 is also at a distance of 1 from its closest prime 2, but the prime 5 is at distance of sqrt(2) from its nearest prime so, a(2) = 5.
%Y A396609 Cf. A000040, A001481, A115258.
